## 🗄️ DATA & API

### Server Actions (preferred for mutations)
```typescript
"use server";

import { z } from "zod";
import { revalidatePath } from "next/cache";

const Schema = z.object({
  title: z.string().min(3),
  content: z.string().min(10),
});

export async function createPost(input: z.infer<typeof Schema>) {
  const validated = Schema.safeParse(input);
  if (!validated.success) return { error: validated.error.flatten() };
  // db operation...
  revalidatePath("/posts");
  return { success: true };
}
```

### tRPC
- Type-safe API routes only
- Always validate input with Zod on the router
- `publicProcedure` vs `protectedProcedure` — never mix up

### Prisma + MongoDB
- `prisma.$transaction` for all multi-step writes
- Never expose Prisma types to client — always create DTO types
- Always use `select` — never fetch full documents

### Prisma Migration Best Practices
- Review generated SQL before applying any migration
- Descriptive names: `add_user_email_index`, `drop_legacy_orders_table`
- Never drop/modify a column without a data preservation plan
- Always test on staging before production
- `prisma migrate dev --create-only` for custom SQL control
- Run `prisma migrate diff` regularly to catch schema drift
- Always have a rollback plan — avoid irreversible operations
- **Never run `prisma migrate reset` in production**

### Prisma Schema Conventions (`**/*.prisma`)
- Always define both sides of a relation with `@relation`
- IDs: `@id @default(autoincrement())` for integers, `@default(cuid())` for strings
- Every model must have:
  ```prisma
  createdAt DateTime @default(now())
  updatedAt DateTime @updatedAt
  ```
- `@@index` for all frequently queried fields
- `@unique` / `@@unique` for uniqueness constraints

